This paper is about spoken language understanding (SLU) in conversational systems, which is a subfield of natural language processing (NLP) and falls under the computer science category of "Computation and Language" (cs.CL). The paper proposes an attention-based network that leverages temporal information and speaker roles for better SLU, which involves machine learning techniques and falls under the sub-category of "Artificial Intelligence" (cs.AI). The paper also evaluates the proposed model on a benchmark dataset, which involves experimental evaluation and falls under the sub-category of "Machine Learning" (cs.LG) and "Software Engineering" (cs.SE). Additionally, the paper focuses on improving the user experience in conversational systems, which involves human-computer interaction (HCI) and falls under the sub-category of "Social and Information Networks" (cs.SD) and "Human-Computer Interaction" (cs.HC).
